    "## 1. Introduction\n",
    "\n",
    "The NeighborList class allows all neighbor atoms within a specified cutoff distance to be identified, and provides a nice interface for accessing each atom's coordination number and list of neighbor atoms. \n",
    "\n",
    "### 1.1. Theory and methodology\n",
    "\n",
    "The NeighborList class uses the nlist() function in atomman/core/nlist.py to built the list of neighbor atoms.  First, the routine defines an orthogonal super-box that fully encompasses the system.  The super-box is then divided into cubic bins with dimensions of cutoff/cmult, where cmult is an integer (default value is 1).  Each bin is given a list of atom ids corresponding to both the real atoms in the system as well as ghost atoms from periodic replicas of the system that fall inside the bin's boundaries.\n",
    "\n",
    "For all bins containing at least one real atom, the shortest vector distance between the atoms within that bin and nearby bins are calculated using dvect().  The ids of atoms separated by less than the cutoff distance are added to each other's neighbors list, as long as the ids are not the same or already in the list.\n",
    "\n",
    "**NOTE 1:** This routine does not differentiate between the different periodic replicas of the atoms.  As such, the system's dimensions should be larger than the cutoff distance used to ensure that atoms are not neighbors of themselves, or periodic replicas of the same atom.\n",
    "\n",
    "**NOTE 2:** The cmult parameter adjusts the bin size as well as the number of nearby bins that are included in the neighbor search.  A larger cmult reduces the total space that needs to be explored, but increases the number of programming loops.  As such, optimum values can depend on how the routine is implemented.  Here, 1 seems to be the most computationally efficent.\n",
    "\n",
    "**NOTE 3:** A new Cython version of the nlist() function is included in atomman version 1.2 that results in considerable speedups over the pure Python implementation.  Even so, the routine is likely not fully implemented and could potentially benefit from further improvement.  "
